author: Paul Hepker
text:
This band makes me soooo happy. This song in particular illustrates what can happen when 19 incredible musicians put aside their egos, and collectively make something so meticulously planned sound so incredibly free and spontaneous and joyful. 

This reminds me of my Brecker Brothers days, the days of Weckl and Pattatucci. And before that - of Michel Colombier‚Äôs ‚ÄúWings‚Äù. Or Klaus Ogermann‚Äôs ‚ÄúSymbiosis‚Äù, Miles‚Äô ‚ÄúBtiches Brew‚Äù. 

But how cool to record this album in front of a live audience? For the band and listeners to feed off of each other. Must have been ecstatic. (I hope I hear about the next one before it happens!)

This may be too slick for some, or too jazzy - but for me it‚Äôs Bach Escher G√∂del - these intricate lines interacting and mirroring and counterpointing, always compelling, always driving. 

This music of Empire Central is alive, and thriving. And heartbreakingly beautiful. Thanks for making me forget - if only for a moment - how lost and divided we are as humans. Capable of great harm and destruction, but also with such an innate capacity for cooperation and co-creation. 

Viva Snarky Puppy!

text:
I'll begin with... I love the band, I started listen to them after their show in Glastonbury a few months ago, it was amazing, but also simpler, and this will be my my point, simplicity.

I'm just a nobody, but I like to share my point of view after comparing this with Glastonbury.

This sounds great, but it's too much, it's hard to process, in my case it's a lot more than my ears can catch, lots of instruments and musicians I can see but their sounds gets lost.

2 drummers, 3 percussionist, 4 guys on keyboards, cyntizaisers, samplers, 3 guitars; it's just overkill; no doubt they are a bunch of genios though.

I'll stay with the smaller version of the band, anytime.

author: sc pk
text:
anyone here experienced being in the actual place of recording?
how does it feel with the headset on?
replies: ['@Randy Simon wow! Such a nice experience - thanks for sharing', 'I was at this recording session.  The headphone mix was quite good.  You needed it because the guitars, bass, keyboards, and violin were all direct fed and made no sound in the room.   Without the phones, all you heard were horns, drums, and percussion.', '@gamzer wow, that is such an incredible experience - thanks for explaining üòÉ', 'I have been in the room, not for this one but for "we like it here". The headphones give you a pretty balanced level and raw mix but it\'s not what you are hearing here. This has been mixed a lot after the fact. But still it\'s pretty damn close in the room from what I remember. It\'s not like they are adding all sorts of sounds in post or anything just really getting everything to sit in the mix. I did find myself taking off my headphones to hear the live sound a few times too particularly to get a sense of the horns and drums in the room.']

author: mark prater
text:
I've been a big fan of Mark Letterie's solo stuff for years. His music is undoubtedly challenging and extremely funky.
What I found, though, was that most of the stuff I like has insane rhythm and drive, it doesn't have much on top in terms of equally interesting melodies.
Well, Dayum.
This track has all that!
I now see the difference between his solo stuff and his Snarky stuff; the horns are smokin' and his licks over the top add the cherry.
In my top 5 of Snarky tracks.
One of the few songs I've ever heard (and that's 60 years of hearing) that continues to gain momentum through to the last note...

But with how judgemental you came across, you're not interested in looking past face value.", 'It was a live album recording session in front of an audience. That audience needed to hear what the band was hearing, and our mix engineers (and the AT50 headphones) did an excellent job ensuring that. The venue was chosen for multiple reasons, both technical and artistic. Thanks for watching.']

author: SkonrokkenTV
text: Ok maybe I see the point...they want the audience to hear what the sound engineer hears or something. But missing the point of live performances.  And using pretty mediocre audio technica headphones as well. Why not just use a better performance space with better acoustics? No can't see the point. But then I'm old fashioned.
replies: ['Half the instruments in the room were inaudible because they were being direct fed. Without headphones, all you heard was percussion and horns.  Like others said, it wasn‚Äôt a concert; it was a recording session that some of us were lucky enough to sit in on.', "If you can't see the point, try to imagine the comparison between what you're hearing here with what the average live show sounds like, and remember that this is an album being recorded."]

author: Butch Ford
text: Hi all, I don't normally comment on anything I watch but, I'm making an exception for this. There's definitely something about the spirit captured in this video! The odd time at the start, the shifts in movement from dark to bright, and Shaun trying his best to hold it all in until the right moment to let go ( that moment around 9:40 minutes or so). I think I've watched it 4 or 5 times now and will absolutely watch more. All I really want to say is, I don't think I've loved music so much as when I was much younger listening to Return To Forever (RIP CHICK!!) You all have revived my zeal for music. THANK YOU!

replies: ['I was there for two of these sessions as well. Everything Nathan DeVol said especially about it being life changing I agree 100%', 'See Shane‚Äôs reply above- this was a live studio audience recording session. We (I attended four of the sessions) the audience where listening in ‚Äòdirectly‚Äô to each of the 19 musicians all at once in our headphones. Obviously there were hot mics for all three percussionists, the three full drum kits and the brass and woodwinds. The sitting down and trying to be respectful and quiet was to reduce audience/ room sounds ending up in the recordings. I can assure you it was not lame. I would better describe it as life affirming and life changing. üòÅ', "lol what? It definitely didn't suck. I was there for two of these sessions."]

replies: ['I was also there. You are missing the point entirely- but, totally cool. I won‚Äôt have to compete with you for tix the next one. üòé', '@Randy Simon Well use amps & wedges then..... The "separation" thing is a myth. It all ends up going in 2 channels. Namely your right & left ears.', '@stretchmorgan I was there. The guitars, keyboards, violin, and bass were inaudible.  They were all direct fed.  If you don‚Äôt believe that, I can‚Äôt help you', "@Randy Simon I don't see a single instrument in that line up that wouldn't have been audible in the room. There's an audience there so in my opinion that's a gig.", 'Assuming you are not just yanking our chains, this was not a gig. It was a recording session and headphones were necessary because half of the instruments were not audible in the room because they were directly feeding into the recording console.  Headphones were the only way to hear all the music - even for the band.']

author: Jon Sheik
text:
Usually, mixdown is hard. Taking 8-128 tracks down to a  stereo or surround image that sounds good across sound systems or in a car, plus adding all the sonic niceties after reverb (which isn't usually that hard), creating the sonic palette from the various performances (basics and dubs)...
...but not all the time. When someone writes a great song, and then it gets arranged beautifully, when there's enough musicians to play the parts live, and when the recordists do an amazing job of capturing each instrument plus the sound of the room, and put that down faithfully on media? The mixdown becomes embarrassingly easy, and you simply bring all the faders up, balance it all, maybe tweak something, maybe not, sit back and smile. I suspect that mixing this was probably like that. :-)

text: No words can really do this justice, just pure Beauty!! Sean's (I believe that's his name) when he just had to scream and let it it out at the end is what I've had to do myself before when jamming/improvising and it's Special like this!! :). So awesome to witness it and I got fucking teary eyed and all, just so intense and relatable to me! :). We are not doing anything, we're just pure conduits/antenna's/vessels, whatever we want to call it and Sean as well as all the guys in the group are so blessed to be that for all of us to enjoy. Watching everyone's elation and just pure Joy after was as or more Special in my humble opinion than the actual performance. Everyone in that room felt that vibration, that energy that is simply overwhelming (in a Great way) at times and Sean just let it out in such a raw way there at the end, that it kind of encapsulated everyone's and the rooms HIGH vibration/energy. Continued Blessings!! :)

author: Musicadamata
text: A question for the musicians here. The risk of mistakes increases as the number of musicians increases to form this Big Band. As there is no sheet music in this performance-recording,  does the producer have a low level risk-aversion or the mistakes are corrected in the edition of the recording? Or do this musicians have an extraordinary memory? Anyway,  Snarky Puppy is the great innovator in instrumental music in this century: a great jazz-pop-rock Big Band. At each release, you wait anxiously for their next great live-studio recording!

Thumbs up", 'Yep, absurdly good work by that crew. These recordings never miss.', 'You guys did your thing ! üíØüëèüëèüëè', "Every Snarky Puppy mix I listen to has this amazing thing; the bottom two octaves. The definition, precision, and solidity of the sonics below A220 and down through A55 are frankly, amazing. From ears, through mic technique and compression and whatever else you're doing...\n...Nic Hard, if I was well I'd assist just for the sheer sonic joy of what you're doing. Room-elimination mics, sub mixes being sent to musicians as cue feeds for them to balance their own cans (I'm sure I had it wrong before lol), you're having *fun!*"]

author: NeedGod dot com
text:
The gospel I would say is the main message of the Bible, it is the work of Jesus Christ, the Son of God and what He did on the cross for all of humanity.

¬† ¬† ¬† But, before talking about Jesus and the cross, we need to look at the problem of humanity, the problem every one of us is faced with. Despite the efforts of any person, we cannot earn our way to heaven. Romans 3:23 says: "For all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God,". Anyone can examine themselves and know that even though, yes, sometimes we can do good, we also do evil at times. We commit moral crimes, and we rebel against God, which the Bible calls sin. We lie, we steal, we blaspheme God, and we can lust and have hate for our brother in our hearts. These are just some of the sins more than likely every person on earth has committed. God is loving, holy and merciful among other attributes but He is also just, perfectly just. Like any crime, sin has to be punished. If God did not punish sin, then He would be unjust. He would be corrupt. Someone has to take the punishment. Romans 6:23 says: "For the wages of sin is death, but the free gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.". This is talking about spiritual death, not physical death; if you die in your sins then you go to hell. There is good evidence that humans have souls. Near-death experiences are one of those evidences. There is a part of you that lives on past your physical body.¬†

¬† ¬† ¬† God sent His only Son to earth about 2000 years ago, His Son is Jesus Christ. Jesus Christ is the promised Savior of the world. He fulfilled hundreds of prophecies by coming to and being in our world. Jesus was born of a virgin, lived a sinless life and was crucified on the cross as a payment for our sins. God poured out His wrath on Jesus in our place, meaning the justice of God is satisfied and sin is punished. While we were still at enmity with God, God still wants to save us, Romans 5:8 says: "But God demonstrates His own love toward us, in that while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us.". Three days after Jesus was crucified, He rose again proving that His payment was enough and that He was who He said He was, the Son of God. There is real-world evidence for the life, death and resurrection of Jesus Christ. This is not just a nice story.

¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† Scripture tells us to repent, to put our trust in Jesus, and to follow Him as Lord. Repentance means a change of mind which means to turn from a life following sin to a life following Christ. Salvation is a free gift and it cannot be earned. No one can be perfectly moral on their own, it is impossible. This is the only way to be in the presence of God in heaven. It is important to reiterate that we cannot save ourselves; it is the gift of God for one to be saved. God is rich in mercy and ready to forgive, cry out to Him, be sincere when coming to God, this is not a flippant thing. Repent and place your trust in Jesus Christ alone, today is the day of salvation. Ephesians 2:8-9 says: "For by grace you have been saved through faith; and that not of yourselves, it is the gift of God; not as a result of works, so that no one may boast.". Salvation is a gift.¬†

¬† ¬† ¬† There is no other way, Jesus Himself said that He is the way, the truth and the life and no one comes to the Father but through Him. Jesus is not just a way, a truth or a life. Romans 10:9 says: "That if you confess with your mouth Jesus as Lord, and believe in your heart that God raised Him from the dead, you will be saved;".

author: Lowness Funk
text:
I love Michael League but there are some things that I cant understand in this recording. 
For instance- It sound like a soundtrack from an 80"s action film.  
What does this music say about  America today and whats happening in our country?  Its seems like its nostalgia instead of saying something in music to connect people .   
Great playing though...
replies: ['@Lowness Funk Right on, and I see your point. However, the headphones were a necessity as this was technically a recording session, albeit in front of a live audience. The audience members had the same mix (essentially) that the band had in ours. So it was very much still a "live" experience - the headphones were used a monitors, as you would in a traditional studio setting, so everyone could hear the band and the band could hear themselves.', "@Mark Lettieri I appreciate your response Mark.  I guess what speaks to me beyond the music is visually- seeing a group of people (musicians and audience) with headphones on enjoying 'live' music.  Live music should travel through the air and hit people in different ways. All those headphone make me think of the current state of humanity and how we all think we are taking part in community via social media but, to me, it just seems in the end everyone has their own headphones on and is checking out their own thing.", 'Interesting. The title comes from the Trinity River, a river that connects the north Texas cities of Fort Worth, Dallas, and Denton - locations that all of the members of SP have either lived or played at some point. Sonically, the influences stem from a combination of Texas blues and rock, and Black gospel music - sounds that greatly impacted me as a non-native Texan who started his career here. That said, the song is probably one of the most "connective" I\'ve ever written. I do enjoy 80\'s action movies, however, which I don\'t necessarily see as a bad thing. But being that it\'s instrumental music, people will hear what they want to in it...Thanks for listening.']

author: Bob Cuesta
text: good stuff.  why so many redundant instruments?
replies: ['@Bob Cuesta Same to you', '@Jason Thomas Have a nice day', "@Bob Cuesta I'm very chill. Didn't say you did, that was a general statement in the point I was making, while answering your question.", "@Jason Thomas ...and no one said what you do or don't need.\nChill, bro.", '@Bob Cuesta No one asks that question when it\'s a big band or marching band. Being redundant means no longer useful or needed. In our case, our reason is about more musical layers and options to serve or create something unique within the music. Instead of thinking it\'s redundant to have 3 percussionists or 3 drummers, Listen to what we were able to do with it. Do we need multiple guitarists/drummers/perc players etc.... No. But again, the focus or reason isn\'t about "do you need" rather it\'s about, what could you do if you have those extra layers and musical options? If it\'s about "creating" then who\'s to say what you do or don\'t need...']

author: Love Is The Only Thing
text:
This makes me happy on so many levels. : )
First, Snarky Puppy is just so much better with a great video production. Seeing them having fun is a real plus to their music. 
Sencond, I was looking forward to hearing new stuff ever since their last album came out.
Third, having Larnell on board is a big win for any band - he is my favorite drummer. 

I also am going to see them on 17th of October this year. Already saw them once in 2019, which was easily my favorite concert I have ever been to, and I have been to lots of them. 
Catch them live if you ever get the chance to do so! 

Sending love to all of you. <3 <3 <3

author: Nicola D'Alicandro
text: Awesome tune from Mark Lettieri! There's something i don't like very much in the mix/master process (too much compression, overall dark sound, muddy drums, some missed hits...) but the groove it's so cool!
replies: ['@JASON THOMAS thanks for all the tips- I‚Äôll dive down those rabbit holes. Have a great tour and I just bought tix to ground up 2023. See ya in Florida next year. üôè', '@Nathan DeVol He‚Äôs also been with the Dan since 00 or 01. Check out the records Two Against Nature(he played the title track + another, can‚Äôt remember the name). But he play on the entire Everything Must Go record. The last Toto record too. Great stuff.', "@Nathan DeVol Oh yeah. Carlock has always been blazing. Met him back in 92, 93 when he lived in Dallas. Became friends and then I started to sub for him, a lot back in those days. That was a lot of fun, as it introduced me to the Top 40/Wedding Band scene in Dfw, guys I still work with to this day when I'm home. Party bands was like heaven to me as I was a 80's kid. Loved Pop, Rock, Classic Rock, Big Band, etc... Those bands gave me the chance to play it all in one night. It also opened up my playing. Can't come behind a guy like that and not bring your Triple A game. Wanted to make sure he'd/those bands called me back. Game changer for me back then. Been such a treat to see him play again and hang with him, since he had a big influence on the way I play. You should check out all the Wayne Krantz stuff he did(go back to like 96) & is still doing. Also Rudder... Has always had his own thing. Amazing player & person...", "@Jason Thomas I bet it's a fun tour - I was also blown away by Keith Carlock. Very interesting looking set up and some really amazing drumming. He wasn't on my radar at all - but is now. Take care - hope to see you all again soon.", "@Nathan DeVol Lolol.... That's Awesome man. Thanks for the kind words and for coming out. Really appreciate that. Glad y'all enjoyed the show. Such a fun tour for us."]

author: Evil√°sio J√∫nior
text: One could argue that 2 drummers, 3 percussionists, 3 keyboardists, 3 guitarists and so on, is all too much... But when you see them playing, it's not at all about being the most virtuos player, it is all about having FUN with friends while playing music and everyone bringing what makes them unique! The one chord or the one sound effect they play is filled with technique and musical thought, but also tons of JOY! They have time to stop playing and just clap along, that's so cool!!!

text: This track has what might be the best Dolby Atmos spatial audio mix I've ever heard over on Apple Music, so be sure to check it out! I'm super hyped for this album! <3
replies: ["@Nic Hard Absolute legends! A year ago I would never have believed I'd see the interest in surround music growing beyond my Steven Wilson Blu-ray collection. Still a long way to go in educating both the average music fan and especially the average mixing engineer, but I think we'll get there! :)", '@Nic Hard Nic Hard, the man himself! Thank you for your amazing work with Snarky Puppy. It has been a huge inspiration for me.', 'Hey Andy, thanks for that.  Fab Dupont and I did it together.  I highly recommend listening on a 7.1.4 setup, it is so much fun', "@Creativical Apple weirdly doesn't make it very obvious but any old pair of stereo headphones will work on a compatible Apple device. On iOS with non-Airpods/Beats you have to change Settings -> Music -> Dolby Atmos to Always On. Atmos mixes when streamed this way receive a special stereo binaural mixdown that only works with headphones, so if you force the setting and use something like your car stereo or bluetooth speakers it will be rough. To answer the original question, I listen with various Airpods and a 5.1.2 living room setup through a Denon AVR and Apple TV.", '@Andy Grundman How did you listen to the mix? For Dolby you need an "Atmos Enabled Device", even when you want to listen with Headphones. So what device(es) do you have?']

Got a text on YouTube (response) from Larnell Lewis !', '@JASON THOMAS God bless Snarky Puppy and all who sail in her!', '@Jeff Stringer We all have parts to play, just like any other section, be it harmonically, rhythmically, or both. This only becomes difficult when egos get in the way. We‚Äôve never had that problem and never will. We‚Äôre All about the music. Period! Thanks for listening/watching.', "They've been doing it for years, man ‚Äì check out their other albums!", "@Jeff Stringer I'm aware. I'm asking how that works in practice.
